cumented as a situation in some locations which is problematic.&#10;Now, you can argue (as ninja did) that parents wouldn't lie, but in fact they do. Not just homeschooling parents, but peope in general. Especially people who are highly motivated to lie, say by having a concrete benefit associated with lying. &#10;*To me what you're describing is the opposite of fair*&#10;What's unfair is students who do not attend a school qualifying to play based on lower or different standards, and hijacking resources allocated for actual students. &#10;Playing is extracurricular. When it robs the actual instruction that an attending child receives, that is seriously unfair, and quite frankly more impactful than your child potentially not being able to play a sport in the academic environment. &#10;*you're saying that only some students are worthy of participating in competitive sports.*&#10;When you participate in a competitive sport, that's actually true anyway. Were there an infinite number of slots on the team Tim Tebow played on? Only some students, like Tim Tebow, were able to play. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1361" language="en" documentId="632" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="stellaluna4" date="09/06/2013" docType="forumpost" origUrl="http://community.babycenter.com/post/a44369503/home_schooling_debate_this_hypothetical?cpg=34" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="632" notes="" title="Home schooling: Debate this hypothetical"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="268"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="269" end="356"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="357" end="600"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="601" end="655"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="55" sofa="1" begin="656" end="822"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="59" sofa="1" begin="823" end="1068"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="63" sofa="1" begin="1069" end="1159"/><type6